properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of heavy rain is forecast for the central coast of British Columbia for Thursday and Friday. A pair of frontal waves will make landfall in succession on the central coast of British Columbia Thursday and Friday. The total rainfall amount from these frontal waves is forecast to be approach 150 mm. The forecast heavy rain on top of antecedent moisture may result in localised flooding or road washouts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of freezing rain is expected. Locations: central and northwestern New Brunswick. Time span: This afternoon and tonight. Remarks: Central New Brunswick (north of the Fredericton area): Periods of light freezing rain or rain is expected to develop this afternoon and persist this evening, becoming just rain by midnight. Although amounts are expected to be light, over high terrain, the freezing rain could last several hours. Northwestern New Brunswick: Periods of light snow or freezing rain are expected to develop this afternoon then change to light freezing rain or rain this evening. Precipitation is expected to change to showers after midnight. In some localities, especially over high terrain, several hours of freezing rain is likely. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: 10 to 15 cm of snow is expected for Highway 97 and the Pine Pass on Thursday. A weather system will move into northern BC early Thursday morning bringing heavy snow to the region.
